      1. <a name="1" id="1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1" title="" id="_ftn1"> </a> Perhaps this fact explains the two major models that  arose to create ICT standards outside of the accredited process during these  years: the &quot;promoter-adopter&quot; model that was very frequently employed  (and still is) in the microprocessor industry, and the incorporated, nonprofit  membership organization that was almost always employed in the software  space.&nbsp; The former model can accurately  be described as a &quot;by invitation only&quot; cross-license, with right to  sub-license, contractual arrangement that usually relates to a single standard,  while the latter is a more flexible creation that usually allows anyone to  join, and which is well suited to create many standards over time.&nbsp; The promoter-adopter model therefore allows  close controls to be maintained over patent rights, while the structure of the  latter usually has a very simple membership application, and therefore must  rely upon the adoption and administration of an IPR policy to address patent  issues.&nbsp; </div>
  <div id="ftn2">
